### First Phase of South Asian Immigration
- Five years from 1906 to 1910 brought more than 12,000 South Asians to the West coast of North America.
- Prime Minister Wilfrid Laurier was hesitant to bar South Asians; the Dominion's connection with the British Raj meant such an action would exacerbate growing tensions.
- Vancouver was the main gateway for Asian immigrants.
- Thomas Guigan (Vancouver city clerk) petitioned Richard William Scott (Dominion's secretary of state) for federal intervention.
- Guigan espoused the "climate theory": South Asians could not perform labor because they were naturally unfitted to stand the climate.
- 19th-century colonial theory: race was a consequence of geography and a determinant of one's fitness for land.
- Federal officials dismissed Guigan's concerns initially.
- However, BC officials grew new arrivals with concern.
- After the Canadian Pacific Railway was completed, many immigrants worked in domestic service.
- Important anti-Asian argument: Medical inspection procedures at BC ports. Quarantine apparatus was used to protect against sick immigrants.
  - *Sick*: an infectious disease acting as a convenient excuse to deny entry to the country.
- South Asians arriving at BC ports in 1906 came on the heel of shifts from regional to federal disease prevention policies.
- Canada began increasing federal-level inspections and mandated quarantines.
- Rise of germ theory confirmed views of the body and its wastes as sites of disease.
  - Brought about the belief that sickness came from the human carrier.
- Galtonian race theories of race categorization endured and transformed immigration policy.
- Medical inspections for migrants were a racialized process from the outset since race could serve as an indication of disease.
- The Immigration Branch began selectively screening for various non-fatal infections.
  - Reappropriation of scientific means of the government to serve political ones.
- Officials warned that BC was becoming the "dumping grounds" for diseased Asians.
- New standardized health screening requirements barred the mute, blind, epileptic, etc.
- All immigrants were required to be vetted by a Board of Inquiry
- Any immigrant found to be reliant on charitable or government assistance within two years would be deported.
- Dominion government initially did little to discourage Indian immigration
  - A slump in Asian immigration in the summer led to a severe scarcity of cheap labor in the province.
- South Asians were aboard most of the CPR vessels from Asia; catalyzed public outcry.

