### Perceptions and Actions
- Public conceptions of India as a land of filth and exotic customs preceded South Asians to BC.
- The "unclean" stereotype did not impact Chinese employment status in the province.
- Medical opinion on South Asians was clouded by generalizations about life in colonial India.
- While A.S. Munro initially wrote the negative medial opinion, Munro began to help South Asians after changing his position.
- Press reports throughout the summer continue to register alarm at the South Asian arrivals.
- Labor unions began to petition Asians not to mix with whites.
- Munro disagreed that Hindus were dirty by nature.
- Dominion government still took no immediate steps towards exclusion.
- "Every wage earner" in BC was in favor of stopping, to some degree, Hindu immigration.
- New claims emerged accusing South Asians had gonorrhea, sodomy, venereal disease.
- Demonstrate tremendous anxiety caused by the entrance of South Asians into the Canadian labor market.
- Labor organizations opposed immigration for economic and ideological reasons. Sexual deviance was understood to be a product of "imagined Oriental licentiousness".
- Contrary to BC popular opinion, at least some were invested in safeguarding their health.
- South Asians appeared dirty from their arrival; thus, morality was construed from this uncleanliness.
- Colonel Falk Warren took issue with racial statements on cleanliness; yet, he was the minority on the issue.
- South Asians began to avoid Canadian ports by October; those who chose to stay found it difficult to meet their needs.
- Health Departments continued to monitor the sanitary conditions of South Asian camps.
- While some residents were sympathetic to camp residents, many were not; "suffering from an invasion of Hindoo beggars".

