### Incident and Outcry
- Dramatic allegation that South Asians gang-raped a white woman in the suburbs.
  - Many reasoned that sexual assault was the inevitable result of allowing South Asians onto the street.
  - While many papers sought to sensationalize the case, there were cracks in the accuser's story.
  - Nevertheless, the alleged rape had a dramatic effect on Vancouver's populace.
  - The newspaper partly retracted the story, as Vancouver police doubted the veracity of the allegations.
  - Nevertheless, the allegation had damaged South Asians' reputations.
- 1914: Jack Kong, a Chinese servant, murdered his employer.
  - The public's first reaction was to attribute Kong's actions to the inherent immorality and violence of his race.
  - Because many households employed Chinese servants, the press asserted that it would be unjust to hold the entire race responsible.

