### United States Involvement
- After several months of protest in BC against South Asians, officials conceded some action was necessary.
- Many South Asians had left to the United States for better wages.
- A significant number of immigrants began entering Washington in 1906.
- Anti-Asian ideology was well-established in the US Pacific coast states.
- California's economic recession of the 1870s sparked an anti-Chinese movement.
- It was argued that the Chinese could not assimilate because of their moral code by threatening domesticity.
- The Japanese victory in the Russo-Japanese war was used to argue that the Japanese were more deceitful.
- The arrival of Hindus inflamed greater menace than the other two groups.
- Because of animosity migrants faced in BC, it was suggested that South Asians would have difficulty succeeding in the US.
- Sharp spike in South Asian immigration in 1906: important but challenging position as guardians of public health.
- 1891 Immigration Act - conflated nativism, bacteriology, eugenics.
- Incoming immigrants were to be issued medical certificates stipulating whether they were diseased.

